04525nam a22005775i 9780822375319DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20152015ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a2015009507  a97808223753197 a10.1515/97808223753192doi  a(DE-B1597)554287  a(OCoLC)915138176  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC00aBT660.C349bS36 2015 4aBT660.C349bS36 2015 7aREL0550002bisacsh04a200.972911 aSchmidt, Jalane D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCachita's Streets :bThe Virgin of Charity, Race, and Revolution in Cuba /cJalane D. Schmidt. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (376 p.) :b27 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aReligious Cultures of African and African Diaspora People00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: "Antes": Processions Past -- tPART I. Cuba Profunda, 1612-1927 -- tChapter 1. From Foundling to Intercessor: Our Lady Help of Slaves -- tChapter 2. Mambisa Virgin: Patrona of the Patria -- tPART II. Regal Streets, 1931-1936 -- tChapter 3. Royalty in Exile: Banishing Bembes -- tChapter 4. Crowning La Caridad: The Queen of Republican Cuba -- tPART III. Martial Streets, 1951-1958 -- tChapter 5. The Virgin General on the March: Conquering Cuba? -- tChapter 6 Rebel Sierras and Lowlands: Petitioning the Mother of Cuba -- tPART IV. Revolutionary Streets, 1959-1998 -- tChapter 7. "¡Todos a la Plaza!": Mobilizing in Revolutionary Time and Space -- tChapter 8. "The Streets Are for Revolutionaries!": Prohibiting Processions -- tChapter 9. Luchando in the Special Period: Papal Visit -- tConclusion: Processions Present: Returning to the Streets, 1998-2012 -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCuba's patron saint, the Virgin of Charity of El Cobre, also called Cachita, is a potent symbol of Cuban national identity. Jalane D. Schmidt shows how groups as diverse as Indians and African slaves, Spanish colonial officials, Cuban independence soldiers, Catholic authorities and laypeople, intellectuals, journalists and artists, practitioners of spiritism and Santería, activists, politicians, and revolutionaries each have constructed and disputed the meanings of the Virgin. Schmidt examines the occasions from 1936 to 2012 when the Virgin's beloved, original brown-skinned effigy was removed from her national shrine in the majority black- and mixed-race mountaintop village of El Cobre and brought into Cuba's cities. There, devotees venerated and followed Cachita's image through urban streets, amassing at large-scale public ceremonies in her honor that promoted competing claims about Cuban religion, race, and political ideology. Schmidt compares these religious rituals to other contemporaneous Cuban street events, including carnival, protests, and revolutionary rallies, where organizers stage performances of contested definitions of Cubanness. Schmidt provides a comprehensive treatment of Cuban religions, history, and culture, interpreted through the prism of Cachita.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aCaridad del Cobre, Virgen de la. 0aRevolutionszCubaxHistory. 7aRELIGION / Christian Rituals & Practice / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071182040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822375319zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822375319423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822375319.jpg  a978-3-11-071182-0  DUK eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles